  1. Question

    A ship sailed 5.1 miles in a direction of 11° North of East. The ship turned and sailed 3.9 miles in a direction 74° North of East.


    The ship’s captain suffers a terrible accident. The first officer radios for help and sets anchor, waiting for help while administering first aid.

    A helicopter, starting where the ship started, wishes to fly directly to the ship. What direction (\(\theta\) rounded to nearest degree) and distance (\(r\) rounded to nearest tenth of a mile) should the helicopter fly?


    • The direction: \(\theta =\)
    • The distance: \(r =\)


    Solution

    Start by naming some lengths (the legs of the two small triangles).


    Evaluate \(a\), \(b\), \(j\), and \(k\). Remember to set your calculator to DEGREE MODE.

    \[a ~=~ 5.1 \cos(11^\circ) ~=~ 5.0062986\] \[b ~=~ 5.1 \sin(11^\circ) ~=~ 0.9731259\] \[j ~=~ 3.9 \cos(74^\circ) ~=~ 1.0749857\] \[k ~=~ 3.9 \sin(74^\circ) ~=~ 3.7489206\]

    Name the lengths of the large triangle.


    Calculate \(x\) and \(y\).

    \[x~=~5.0062986+1.0749857~=~6.0812843\] \[y~=~0.9731259+3.7489206~=~4.7220465\] Calculate \(\theta\). Remember to set your calculator to DEGREE MODE.

    \[\theta ~=~ \arctan\left(\frac{4.7220465}{6.0812843}\right) ~=~ 37.8289231^\circ ~\approx~ 38^\circ\]

    Calculate \(r\) by using Pythagorean Theorem.

    \[r ~=~ \sqrt{6.0812843^2+4.7220465^2} ~=~ 7.6993339 ~\approx~ 7.7 ~\mathrm{mi}\]

    Instead of using Pythagorean Theorem, you could have used trigonometry.

    \[r ~=~ \frac{6.0812843}{\cos(37.8289231^\circ)} ~=~ \frac{4.7220465}{\sin(37.8289231^\circ)} ~=~ 7.6993339 ~\approx~ 7.7~\mathrm{mi}\]
